<font color="#FF0000">ANSWERS ARE NEVER SIMPLE</font><br>
<tt>Sat Jan  3 12:52:10 US/Eastern 1998
</tt><p>
John is right.  We were there for many reasons and some are not yet ready for release and probably never will be.  The general public focused on the Vietnam War because of the news.  The War we were fighting before Vietnam and after, the nuclear cold war continued and at a heightened level.<br><br>
That area of the country was important strategically before and after the war.  Is it important now, probably not, because things change?<br><br>
Did we lose?  The fact that Vietnam stays contained is victory enough.  Cambodia another case.  We now have the capability to keep contained as we see fit.  Case in point Korea.  The collapse of the Soviet Union.  The big picture.  For those who placed their faith in the bear, tough.<br><br>
We always focus on the reasons to fight war as human rights or ideology.  Vietnam as the Japanese thought was an excellent place to control vast riches and strategically located sea-lanes and countries.  Only after the war was going on did the American machine understand the economic importance of the war effort and the protestor who stayed home benefited the most.  Hard pill to swallow I am sure, but where would you be today without the war and the overall effects.  History.<br><br>
This military machine effort is still a huge chunk of the GNP that gives us our easy living.<br><br>
It is tiring to listen to the same old rhetoric, but also know that complete answers can not be given.  We were in Vietnam for complex reasons that necessitated a commitment.  Capitulation has never been the method of a great nation regardless of the ideas of a confused and less dedicated minority of citizens.<br><br>
The question to be answered would be when it was apparent Vietnam was no longer important and their industrial capabilities destroyed why was the departure so difficult.  As a world power weakness or the perception of weakness is all that is needed to bring lessor adversaries to your door.<br>

